04920nam a22008655i 9781501514364DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020miu    fo  d z      eng d  a2020940971  a97815015143647 a10.1515/97815015143642doi  a(DE-B1597)522829  a(OCoLC)1202461400  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amiucUS-MI 7aLIT0110002bisacsh  aHH 5086qDE-25/sred212rvk0(DE-625)rvk/49597:1 aFruoco, Jonathan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aChaucer’s Polyphony :bThe Modern in Medieval Poetry /cJonathan Fruoco. 1aKalamazoo, MI : bMedieval Institute Publications, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (XIII, 228 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aResearch in Medieval and Early Modern Culture ;v2900tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tContents -- tNotes on the Texts and Translations -- tAbbreviations of Chaucer’s Works -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. Polyphony and Multilingualism in Medieval England -- tChapter 2. Fin’amor, Stil Novo: Chaucer’s Early Influences -- tChapter 3. Narrative Evolution and New Discursive Strategies -- tChapter 4. Troilus and Criseyde and the Ambiguity of Double Enunciation -- tChapter 5. Hybridization and the Legend of Chaucer’s Inventiveness -- tChapter 6. Extradiegetic Dialogue in The Canterbury Tales -- tConclusion -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGeoffrey Chaucer has long been considered by the critics as the father of English poetry. However, this notion not only tends to forget a huge part of the history of Anglo-Saxon literature but also to ignore the specificities of Chaucer’s style. Indeed, Chaucer’s decision to write in Middle English, in a time when the hegemony of Latin and Old French was undisputed (especially at the court of Edward III and Richard II), was consistent with an intellectual movement that was trying to give back to European vernaculars the prestige necessary to a genuine cultural production, which eventually led to the emergence of romance and of the modern novel. As a result, if Chaucer cannot be thought of as the father of English poetry, he is, however, the father of English prose and one of the main artisans of what Mikhail Bakhtin called the polyphonic novel.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 4aChaucer. 4aMittelenglisch. 4aModernität. 4aPolyphonie. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aGeoffrey Chaucer.  aMiddle English.  aModernity.  aPolyphony.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package 2020z978311069627108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package English 2020z978311069628808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Englishz978311070474708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020z9783110704532oZDB-23-DKU0 cEPUBz97815015140430 cprintz978150151849240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150151436440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501514364423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501514364.jpg  a978-3-11-069627-1  DG Ebook Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-069628-8  DG Ebook Package English 2020b2020  a978-3-11-070471-6  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishb2020  a978-3-11-070474-7  EBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Englishb2020  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17S